               <p>MARY FOWLER. I am a <rs id="t18250630-36-viclabel179" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250630-36-victim257 t18250630-36-viclabel179"></join>, and keep a shop in <placeName id="t18250630-36-crimeloc180">Castle-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250630-36-crimeloc180" type="placeName" value="Castle-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250630-36-crimeloc180" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250630-36-off177 t18250630-36-crimeloc180"></join>. On the 26th of May I was in the room behind my shop, and heard the rattling of half-pence; I went into the shop and found the prisoner there - the till was taken out of its place and stood in a chair - I took hold of him; he tried to get away - I called for help and the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182506300016"></xptr>watchman came and took him: there was a crown, a half-crown, some sixpences and shillings in the till.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250630-36-person258">
                  THOMAS 
                  WEBB
               <interp inst="t18250630-36-person258" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250630-36-person258" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250630-36-person258" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman. I heard the cry of Thief! and took the prisoner; he told me next morning that he did it for want.</p>
